[Student "S"]
{When you have 4 cards in both Majors you respond 2\H to a Stayman request. Partner now bids 3NT.   

When you have 4 cards in both Majors you respond 2\H to a Stayman request. Partner now bids 3NT.   

Partner denies having 4 \Hs so he must have 4 \Ss (or he would not have used Stayman). You correct the contract to4\S.

North plays 4\S. East leads the \H2. West grabs the opening lead with the \HA and plays the \D10.

Loser List: \S = 1 : \H = 1 : \D = 1 : \C = 1 :: Total = 4

The \S, \H and \C losers are inevitable so you'd better not lose a \D. Even though West has returned a \D it is still possible that he holds the \DK so the finesse has a chance of working. Let's say a 50% chance. Do you take it? 

No, of course not. Not when you have a play that offers almost a 100% chance. Win the \DA, play \SK, \SA, then \H K Q, discarding dummy's 2 \D losers.  

With one master trump still out you start on the \Cs, playing first the \CK, then overtake the \CJ with dummy's \CQ. The defense is welcome to take their \CA whenever they want, and they are also welcome to their trump trick. You are so gracious because you have your ten tricks!

Half the time the \DK will be with West, and the inferior plan of taking the finesse will work. On those Deals your superior plan shows no payoff.

But the other 50% of the time East will have the \DK. On those Deals you get your just reward.}
[Play "W"]H2

